1) Introduction

This dataset analyzes the airplane landings at SFO International Airport. The data has been obtained from DataSF, a website that tracks different types of data in San Francisco. This data is publicly available to help enhance decision making. The dataset was received from here. I picked this dataset because I love to travel and have been to SFO many times as it is my local airport. I was interested in analyzing the air traffic at SFO in relation to where the flight is departing from, the total weight of the flight, the type of aircraft, and the manufacturer of the aircraft.

Bills, Terry. San Francisco Airports Dynamic Twin Has Transformed Operations. Esri, 21 Oct.2021, esri.com/about/newsroom/blog/san-francisco-airport-bim-gis-processes/. Accessed 07 Nov.2023.

2) Data Preparation

I downloaded the csv file and then imported it into the Rmarkdown. As for processing, the main step I had to take was renaming the variables so that there were no spaces in them. I made 3 new variables. The first one was Total_Landed_Weight_In_Millions. I made this variable because the original variable had values that were very big and would be harder to handle later on in terms of graphing and analyzing. The second variable I made was Continent. I made this variable because my report investigates the relationship between the aircraft manufacturer and continent. The last variable I created was a month variable which is later investigated in this report. A challenge I faced while preparing my data was the amount of data there is in the data set. I had to take time to understand each variable and how it functions in the data set. In terms of NA values, I dropped the rows that contained them. This is because I would not be able to analyze these rows. My data set now has 16,115 observations with 16 variables.

3) Variable Descriptions

Name Type Description
Activity_Period Numeric Year and month at which the landing activity took place
Operating_Airline Character Operator name of the aircraft with passenger, cargo, or landing activity
Operating_Airline Character International Air Transport Association two-letter designation for the Operating Airline
Published_Airline Character Name of Airline that issues ticket and books revenue for aircraft
Published_Airline_IATA_Code Character International Air Transport Association two-letter designation for the Publsihed Airline
GEO_Summary Character Designates whehter the passenger, cargo, or landings activity in relation to SFO arrived from a domestic or international location
GEO_Region Character Detailed breakdown of Geo Summary designating the region from which the aircraft departed from
Landing_Aircraft_Type Character Type of aircraft landed (freighters, passenger, or combi)
Aircraft_Body_Type Character Determines whether aircraft is a wide body, narrowbody, regional, or prpeller operated aircraft
Aircraft_Manufacturer Character Manufacturer name of aircraft
Aircraft_Model Character Model of aircraft designated by manufacturer
Aircraft_Version Character Variation of Aircraft Model (dash number) used to segregate uniqeu version of same model
Landing_Count Numeric Number of aircaft landings
Total_Landed_Weight Numeric Total Landed Weight
Continent Character Continent from which aircraft departed from
Month Character Coresponding Month for Activity
Total_Landed_Weight_In_Millions Numeric Total Landed Weight In Millions

4) Univariate Analyses

Graph 1

This graph displayed a histogram of the Total Landed Weight In Millions for each plane type. The histogram is skewed right with a mean of 18.4. The maximum total weight landed is 267.3 and the minimum total landed weight in millions is 0.01.

Graph 2

This bar graph shows the number of planes that arrived from a domestic location and the number of planes that arrived from an international location. 8092 arrived from a domestic location or 50.2% of planes. 8023 or 49.8% of planes arrived from an international location.

Graph 3

This histogram shows the landing count of each plane type at SFO Airport. It is skewed right with a mean of 112.55. The maximum number of times a plane type landed is 2245.

Graph 4

This bar graph shows the number of planes that are Combi, Freighter, or Passenger planes. As seen by the graph majority of the planes that landed are passenger aircrafts. 142 are Combi or 0.9% of planes. 2021 or 12.5% of planes are freighter. 13952 are Passenger or 86.6% of planes.

5) Multivariate Analyses

Graph 1

This plot graphs the proportion of each airplane type that is international and its average total weight. The correlation coefficient is 0.06. This means that there is a weak relationship between the proportion of international planes for each airline and its average weight.

6) Reproducibility

To ensure reproducibility in my code I made sure that the csv file and picture were both uploaded to github. I made sure to comment my code so that it would easily traceable. I also tried to use packages that users would already have downloaded on their systems so that they would not have to install packages. I made my code sequential so that it would be easy to understand.

7) Choice Elements

The first choice element I included was formatting a string variable. All of my variable names included spaces in them and in order to reference them easily throughout the code, I changed the variable names to have underscores instead of spaces. I also created 3 new variables of interest. This was the Total Weight of the aircraft in millions, continent, and month. I created the first one because the weight values when recorded raw were ver large and would become hard to handle. I created a continent variable because I wanted to generalize the region variable further while analyzing the location an aircraft departed from. The last variable helped me analyze the relationship between domestic and international flights in relation to the month. I used string formatting here too. These elements showed up in the second section of my report. The third element I used was a loop. This showed up while I was creating my continent variable as well as when I was trying to find the percentage of international flights for each airline. I used if statements also while creating my continent variable. Finally, I used inline code throughout my report while describing statistics of graphs.

8) Conclusion

For Univariate graphs I graphed the Total Landed Weight in Millions, number of flights that were domestic or international, landing count, and the aircraft type. I expected the Total Landed Weight graph to be skewed right because most planes will have weights around the same amount and then it will taper off. I expected the amount of planes coming from a domestic or international location to be around the same because San Francisco is an airport that supports both international and domestic landings. For landing count per plane type the graph was skewed right. Finally, I expected the amount of passenger planes to be the most common aircraft type landing at SFO because it mostly supports passengers.

For the Multivariate graphs I expected that there would be a positive correlation between the percentage of international planes and the average total landing weight. However, the graph had a correlation coefficient of 0.06 signifyng a very weak relationship. In the second graph the bar having planes departing from a region in North America had the most variation in aircraft manufacturers. I found it suprising that 100% of South Americas aircrafts were manufactured by Boeing. I found it surprising that freighter planes had a variety in aircraft body types. I expectd it to be mostly wide body planes as they would be able to carry the most cargo. Finally, I expected the amount of international flights to be drastically more during the summer months because people travel more. However, the difference between the number of domestic and international flights was not as drastic as I expected. However the influx of domestic flights during November surprised me, but it made sense as many people travel to be with their families during Thanksgiving.
